By the universal properties of colimits and of
 limits, it suffices to define components \operatorname *{lim}_{J} F(i, -)\to   \operatorname *{colim}_I F(-, j) for each i\in  I,j\in  J which commute with the images of
 maps in I and J. The jth leg of the limiting cone is a map
 \operatorname *{lim}_J F(i, -)\to  F(i, j), while the ith coleg of the colimiting
 cocone is a map F(i, j)\to  \operatorname *{colim}_ F(-, j). The composite defines
 the desired map. The commutativity properties are by construction: for
 instance, compatibility with maps j\xrightarrow {f} j' in J asserts that 




